  "timeboxMinutes": 25,
  "prompt": "Finance wants weekly spend totals across all transactions.\n\nWrite `weekly_spend(base_url, token)`. Fetch every transaction, bucket each transaction into the week whose Monday contains that transaction's date, and sum `amount_cents` per week.\n\nReturn contract:\n\n- Return `dict[str, int]`.\n- Keys are Monday ISO date strings, e.g. `\"2026-04-06\"`.\n- Values are total integer cents spent in that Monday-through-Sunday week.\n- Omit weeks with no transactions.\n- Return `{}` if there are no transactions.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\n2026-04-06 Monday    amount 100 -> bucket \"2026-04-06\"\n2026-04-12 Sunday    amount 200 -> bucket \"2026-04-06\"\n2026-04-13 Monday    amount 300 -> bucket \"2026-04-13\"\n\nreturn {\"2026-04-06\": 300, \"2026-04-13\": 300}\n```\n\nEndpoint details:\n\n- `GET /v1/transactions` is paginated and requires auth.\n- Transaction timestamps are ISO strings; use the date part `timestamp[:10]`.\n- In Python, `date.weekday()` returns `0` for Monday and `6` for Sunday.\n\nThe test harness passes `token` into your function. Do not define or hardcode it; use the `token` parameter when building the `Authorization` header.\n\nInvariants and corner cases:\n\n- Sunday belongs to the previous Monday's bucket.\n- Do not group by calendar month or by the transaction's own date string.\n- Sum integer cents exactly; do not use floating point dollars.\n- Fetch every transaction page.\n\nShared fake API note: this uses the in-process `requests` mock described in the Ramp Travel module guide; there is no real network.\n\nValidation focus: Monday week starts, Sunday boundary, exact cent totals, empty input, and pagination.",
  "signature": {
    "name": "weeklySpend",
    "inputs": [
      {
        "name": "base_url",
        "type": {
          "type": "string"
        }
      },
      {
        "name": "token",
        "type": {
          "type": "string"
        }
      }
    ],
    "output": {
      "type": "object"
    }
  },
